NEWCASTLE DISEASE - BRAZIL
****************************
A ProMED post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
Newcastle disease, imported wild birds - Brazil (Parana)
990823212031
Source: OIE Reports
See also: 20 August 1999
Emergency report
Translation of an e-mail received on 25 August 1999 from Dr
Aluisio Berbert Sathler, Director, Department of Animal Defence,
Ministry of Agriculture and Supply, Brasilia:
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 23 August 1999.
Outbreaks:
Location Japeri, Rio de Janeiro
No. of outbreaks 1
Description of affected population: small, non-commercial property
used as a weekend home by the owner's family. The birds (hens,
roosters, chicks, ducks, geese, and Angola hens [guinea-fowl)
were free-range or kept in pens. No new animals have been
introduced during the past three months. All the birds were born on
the property.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
species: avian
susceptible: 150
cases: 100
deaths: 100
destroyed: 0
slaughtered: 50
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: Ministry of Agriculture
Regional Animal Health Laboratory, Lara, Campinas, Sao Paulo.
B. Diagnostic tests used: intracerebral pathogenicity index =1.42.
C. Causal agent: Newcastle disease virus, pathogenic strain.
Control measures during reporting period:
- stamping out;
- epidemiological surveillance in the neighbouring properties.
................................tg/jw
